evaluation.response:
Adding a banana to your breakfast and experiencing improved energy is a positive step in the right direction.&#x20;

To avoid feeling like you're overcompensating, try focusing on overall nutritional balance rather than the calorie count of individual foods. Prioritize whole, nutrient-dense foods like fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, and whole grains, and aim to include a variety of these at each meal.

Also, try to reframe your mindset around food and nutrition. Instead of seeing certain foods as "allowed" or "forbidden" based on the specific calories or nutrients, try to focus on the beneficial aspects of different foods.

For example, you might think of bananas as a source of potassium and carbohydrates that can help fuel your workouts and support your recovery.&#x20;

By focusing on the positive aspects of different foods and aspiring for overall balance, you can help shift away from an overly restrictive mindset and instead develop a healthier, more positive relationship with food and your body.
